  "type": "Subsection",
  "number": "1.6.2",
  "title": "Velocity",
  "body": " Velocity   Velocity is a vector quantity, which means it includes both magnitude and direction. The magnitude of velocity is speed.  While speed tells you how fast an object is moving, velocity tells you how fast and in which direction. For example, a car moving north at 60 km\/h has a different velocity than the same car moving south at 60 km\/h, even though their speeds are the same.  "
